key "2006ApJ...645..792T"

\end_inset

 has provided a good approximation of the Voigt function better than 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 % fit for temperature 
\begin_inset Formula $T>2$
\end_inset

 K for all x.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Three components of the hydrogen atom velocities are included in the code.
 They are the Hubble velocity 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}_{Hubble}$
\end_inset

, the macroscopic peculiar velocity 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}_{peculiar}$
\end_inset

, and the thermal velocity 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}_{thermal}$
\end_inset

.
 The total velocity of the atom can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}_{tot}=\mathbf{v}_{Hubble}+\mathbf{v}_{peculiar}+\mathbf{v}_{thermal}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After several tests, we figured out that the Ly 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 scattering frequency is very sensitive to the velocity values.
 The Hubble expansion velocity can be exactly calculated at any point in
 the simulation system using the equation 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}_{Hubble}=H\mathbf{r}$
\end_inset

.
 However the peculiar velocity of the gas element is given from the 3D cosmology
 simulation result cell by cell.
 So we performed 3D linear velocity interpolation of the peculiar velocity
 at every point of event.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The dimensionless thermal velocity of the atom is defined 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}=\mathbf{v}_{thermal}/v_{th}$
\end_inset

.
 The thermal velocity component parallel (
\begin_inset Formula $u_{\parallel})$
\end_inset

 to the incident photon direction is drawn from the probability function
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f(u_{\parallel})=\frac{a}{\pi H(a,x)}\frac{e^{-u_{\parallel}^{2}}}{(u_{\parallel}-x)^{2}+a^{2}}.\label{eq:vel-par}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The Ly 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 photon has very high probability of being scattered by a photon having
 velocity 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{\parallel}=x$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After drawing a velocity from Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:vel-par"

\end_inset

, another velocity component is drawn from the Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:vel-per"

\end_inset

.
 The thermal velocity component 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{\perp}$
\end_inset

 is perpendicular to the incident photon direction and lies on the plane
 spanned by the photon initial direction vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{n}_{i}$
\end_inset

 and the final direction vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{n}_{f}$
\end_inset

.
 The thermal velocity component 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{\perp}$
\end_inset

 obeys 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f(u_{\perp})=\frac{1}{\sqrt{\pi}}e^{-u_{\perp}^{2}}.\label{eq:vel-per}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 We put the atom velocity before scattering as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}_{i}$
\end_inset

, the atom's final velocity as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}_{f}$
\end_inset

, and the velocity difference before and after scattering as 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

.
 After scattering, the atom's final velocity 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}_{f}$
\end_inset

 becomes 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}_{f}=\mathbf{v}_{i}+\delta\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 in the global frame of the scattering.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When the Ly 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 photon scatters off an neutral hydrogen atom, we calculate the photon frequency
 in the atom rest frame 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{atom}$
\end_inset

.
 As the photon propagates 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

, the frequency is updated at every cell considering the peculiar velocity
 and the Hubble velocity.
 The photon's initial frequency is 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{i}$
\end_inset

 in the global frame with the propagating direction 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{n_{i}}$
\end_inset

.
 After scattering the photon moves to the direction 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{n_{f}}$
\end_inset

 with final frequency 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{f}$
\end_inset

 .
 Using the unitless frequency parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, the photon's final frequency in the global frame is given as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
x_{f}=x_{i}-\frac{v_{tot,\parallel}}{v_{th}}(1-\cos\theta)+\frac{v_{tot,\perp}}{v_{th}}\sin\theta+g(1-\hat{n_{i}}\centerdot\hat{n_{f}}).
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The angle between 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{n}_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{n}_{f}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{n}_{i}\centerdot\hat{n}_{f}=\cos\theta$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{n}_{\perp}\centerdot\hat{n}_{f}=\sin\theta$
\end_inset

.
 The recoil factor is 
\begin_inset Formula $g=h\nu_{0}/m_{H}cv_{th}$
\end_inset

, where h is the Planck constant.
 The recoil term can change the frequency by transferring atom's momentum
 to the photon.
 We include the term in the Ly 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 scattering code, widely ignored in previous studies.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Methods: Ly 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
