\begin_layout Standard
The procedure of the Ly 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 scattering simulation using Monte Carlo method is described below.
 We calculate the Ly 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 scattering in the global frame.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(1) Set grid for the simulation following the 3D reionization simulation
 results.
 Read density, ionization fraction, peculiar velocity, and temperature fields
 from the 3D reionization simulation results.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(2) Choose the initial frequency 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{i}$
\end_inset

, the position 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{r}_{i}$
\end_inset

, and the direction 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{n}_{i}$
\end_inset

 of the photon.
 We choose the monochromatic line center frequency for the initial frequency
 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 The photon can be emitted from the brightest source in the simulation box.
 The photon's initial direction 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{n}_{i}$
\end_inset

 is drawn isotropically in the simulation.
 The thermal velocity 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{th}=\sqrt{\frac{2k_{B}T}{m_{H}}}$
\end_inset

 and unitless frequency 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

 is calculated using the parameters at the given position.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(3) Draw a random optical depth from the scattering probability 
\begin_inset Formula $P(\tau)=e^{-\tau}$
\end_inset

.
 The photon can propagate the optical depth 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 before it scatters.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(4) Convert 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 to the proper distance 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

.
 To do this in the cell based system, we move a small amount of physical
 distance 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{small}$
\end_inset

 to direction 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{n_{i}}$
\end_inset

.
 We define 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{small}=0.001\;\times$
\end_inset

 cell size.
 Calculate the corresponding optical depth 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{small}=5.899\times10^{-14}\left(\frac{T}{1000K}\right)^{-0.5}\int_{0}^{l_{small}}n_{H}(s)H(a,x)ds$
\end_inset

 using frequency, density, peculiar velocity, Hubble velocity, temperature,
 and the ionization fraction at the given point.
 The velocity should be calculated at every point.
 Check the photon location.
 If the photon moves to the next cell, then update all the relevant physical
 parameters.
 Add up the 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{small}$
\end_inset

 until the intended 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 has reached, the corresponding 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 is the physical distance.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(5) Determine the new position vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{r}_{f}$
\end_inset

 with the direction vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{n_{i}}$
\end_inset

 and the physical distance, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{r}_{f}=\mathbf{r}_{i}+l\hat{n}_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(6) Draw a thermal velocity vector 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{\parallel}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{\perp}$
\end_inset

 following their distribution functions at the new position with current
 x.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(7) Draw a new direction vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{n}_{f}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{n}_{f}$
\end_inset

 is drawn isotropically
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(8) Calculate the final frequency 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{f}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{f}$
\end_inset

 using 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}_{Hubble}$
