\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We develop the Ly 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 scattering Monte Carlo code to trace scattering histories of Ly 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 photons in the intergalactic medium of the reionized universe.
 The Ly 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 scattering code can be applied to any 3D cell based cosmology reionization
 simulation data.
 The Ly 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 scattering code can be used to reionization simulation results with arbitrary
 geometry, redshift, source distributions, density, velocity, ionization
 fraction, and temperature.
 We did not use any acceleration schemes generally used in previous studies.
 We accurately computed the optical depth in an expanding cosmological medium.
 We deal with the frequency in high precision to get the precise results.
 Velocity terms affect strongly on frequency, so we calculate the velocity
 accurately at every point along the photon ray.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We build up the code, and test the code against problems having analytic
 solutions.
 A monochromatic source in a static, uniform, isothermal slab (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "1990ApJ...350..216N"

\end_inset

;
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "1973MNRAS.162...43H"

\end_inset

) or sphere (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "2006ApJ...649...14D"

\end_inset

) are tested with the code.
 To make a static gas condition in a cell based code, we hold the Hubble
 expansion velocity, and add peculiar velocity with the same magnitude and
 opposite direction.
 The emergent spectrum shows good fit to what analytic model expects.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We test the code by comparing results with already published references
 with simple geometry and kinematics (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "2002ApJ...578...33Z,2006ApJ...645..792T,2006ApJ...649...14D,2009ApJ...696..853L"

\end_inset

).
 Collapsing and expanding sphere is tested and compared with results in
 the references.
 In this case, the peculiar velocity field set to 0 everywhere, and the
 Hubble velocity actualize the expanding or collapsing sphere.
 The emergent spectrum and their dependency on physical parameters agree
 to the previous results.
 These tests indicates the Ly 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 scattering code is credible.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We apply the code to the 3D cell based reionization simulation and examine
 the constraints of the reionzation processes.
 We present the emergent spectrum by applying the Ly 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 scattering code to the 3D cosmology simulation.
 We apply the code to CODA-II simulation.
 The data contains 3D mass, temperature, pressure, density, ionization fraction,
 velocities of gas field, ionizing flux density, dark matter density field,
 a list of the star particles.
 CODA simulated from 
\begin_inset Formula $z=150$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $z=4.3$
\end_inset

, and snapshots were taken every 10 Myrs.
 We obtain the emergent spectrum using density, peculiar velocity field,
 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

, ionization field, and temperature fields.
 We use cutout box data of the full simulation.
 The size of the cutout data is 
\begin_inset Formula $512^{3}$
\end_inset

 cells, 8 Mpc/h.
 
\end_layout

